# Relational data with dm: Cheat sheet

[For
printing](https://dm.cynkra.com/dev/articles/cheatsheet/cheatsheet-printable.md)

> If you have more than one table, use dm.

##  Create dmâ€¦

###  from database: `dm_from_con()`

``` r
con <- DBI::dbConnect(...)
dm_from_con(con)
```

![](data:image/svg+xml;base64,)

###  from data frames: `dm(df1, df2, ...)`

``` r
dm(df1, df2, df3)
```

![](data:image/svg+xml;base64,)

###  from dm: `dm(dm1, df1...)`

``` r
dm(dm1, df1)
```

![](data:image/svg+xml;base64,)

``` r
dm(dm1, dm2)
```

![](data:image/svg+xml;base64,)

### Add keys: `dm_add_pk()`, `dm_add_fk()`

**Automatic** for MariaDB, SQL Server, Postgres, and others.

####  Primary keys

**Identify** potential primary keys:

- [`dm_enum_pk_candidates()`](https://dm.cynkra.com/dev/reference/dm_enum_pk_candidates.md):
  columns, candidate, why.

**Add** primary keys:

``` r
dm1 |>
  dm_add_pk(table, columns)
```

![](data:image/svg+xml;base64,)

**Identify** potential foreign keys:

- [`dm_enum_fk_candidates()`](https://dm.cynkra.com/dev/reference/dm_enum_fk_candidates.md):
  columns, candidate, why.

**Add** foreign keys:

``` r
dm1 |>
  dm_add_fk(table, column)
```

![](data:image/svg+xml;base64,)

###  dm objects: relational data models

The dm package provides a **grammar of relational data models**. It
helps maintain **referential integrity**.

A dm behaves like a list of tables (data frames or lazy tables)
capturing **relationships** between the tables.

Shiny app: `dm_gui(dm = dm1)`

![Screenshot of the Shiny app provided by dm. It has three parts. On the
left is a diagram view of the dm that one can click to, for instance,
select tables or change their colors. On the right, there is the
generated code as well as a menu to control primary and foreign
keys.](cheatsheet-figures/shiny.png)

##  Resize dm

### Select tables: `dm_select_tbl(dm1, ...)`

``` r
dm1 |>
  dm_select_tbl(-df3)
```

![](data:image/svg+xml;base64,)

### Rename tables: `dm_rename_tbl(dm1, ...)`

### Select columns: `dm_select(dm1, table, ...)`

Automatic update of dm meta-information and table relations.

``` r
dm1 |>
  dm_select(df3, -c3, -c4)
```

![](data:image/svg+xml;base64,)

### Rename columns: `dm_rename(dm1, table, ...)`

### Filter rows: `dm_filter(dm1, table = (pred))`

Filter rows in the table where the condition is defined, but also all
directly/indirectly connected tables.

``` r
dm1 |>
  dm_filter(df3 = (x == "val"))
```

![](data:image/svg+xml;base64,)

##  Visualize dm: `dm_draw()`

### Control diagram level of detail: displayâ€¦

- Only keys (default): `dm_draw(view_type = "keys_only")`.
- All variables: `dm_draw(view_type = "all")`.
- Only table names: `dm_draw(view_type = "title_only")`.

``` r
dm |>
  dm_draw(
    view_type = "title_only",
    rankdir = "TB"
  )
```

![](data:image/svg+xml;base64,)

### Control diagram scope

To visualize fewer tables first use
[`dm_select_tbl()`](https://dm.cynkra.com/dev/reference/dm_select_tbl.md).

### Control diagram colors: `dm_set_colors()`

``` r
dm |>
  dm_set_colors(
    pink = flights,
    orange = starts_with("air")
  ) |>
  dm_draw()
```

![](data:image/svg+xml;base64,)

------------------------------------------------------------------------

##  Data checks

### `dm_examine_constraints()`

tibble with information about which key constraints are met or violated.

### `dm_examine_cardinalities()`

tibble with information about the cardinality of the foreign keys
constraints.

### `check_key(df, col1)`

returns an error if not an unique key.

### `check_subset(df1, df2)`

returns an error if `df1` is not a subset of `df2`.

### `check_set_equality(df1, df2)`

returns an error if `df1` and `df2` are not the same sets.

------------------------------------------------------------------------

###  Fix column names: `dm_disambiguate_cols()`

`dm_disambiguate_cols(dm1)` ensures that all columns in a dm have unique
names.

##  Transform dm into tibble

### Wide tibble: Cascade joins with `dm_flatten_to_tbl()`

Only direct neighbours:
[`dm_flatten_to_tbl()`](https://dm.cynkra.com/dev/reference/dm_flatten_to_tbl.md)

``` r
dm1 |>
  dm_flatten_to_tbl(
.start = df1
)
```

![](data:image/svg+xml;base64,)

All neighbours: `dm_flatten_to_tbl(.recursive = TRUE)`

``` r
dm1 |>
  dm_flatten_to_tbl(
.start = df1,
.recursive = TRUE
)
```

![](data:image/svg+xml;base64,)

### Single tibble dm: `dm_wrap_tbl()`

Parent tables are packed â€”
[`dm_pack_tbl()`](https://dm.cynkra.com/dev/reference/dm_pack_tbl.md).

Child tables are nested â€”
[`dm_nest_tbl()`](https://dm.cynkra.com/dev/reference/dm_nest_tbl.md).

``` r
dm1 |>
  dm_wrap_tbl(
root = green_df
)
```

![](data:image/svg+xml;base64,)

### Retrieve one table of the dm: `pull_tbl()`

``` r
dm1 |>
  pull_tbl(
dm1,
green_df,
keyed = TRUE
)
```

![](data:image/svg+xml;base64,)

If the dm is zoomed, retrieve zoomed table automatically.

``` r
dm1 |>
  dm_zoom_to(green_df) |>
pull_tbl()
```

![](data:image/svg+xml;base64,)

##  Mutate, create, analyze tables

###  Method 1: deconstruct and reconstruct

1.  `dm_get_tables(keyed = TRUE)`:  
    to keep information on primary and foreign keys).

``` r
dm_tbl <- dm1 |>
  dm_get_tables(keyed = TRUE)
```

![](data:image/svg+xml;base64,)

2.  tidyverse pipeline on the table of interest.

``` r
new_table1 <- dm_tbl$table1 |>
  mutate(...)
```

![](data:image/svg+xml;base64,)

3.  Optional: update the dm object:

``` r
dm1 |>
  dm_select_tbl(-table1) |>
  dm(table1 = new_table1)
```

![](data:image/svg+xml;base64,)

###  Method 2: zoom

1.  [`dm_zoom_to()`](https://dm.cynkra.com/dev/reference/dm_zoom_to.md):
    Zoom on a table.

``` r
zoomed_dm1 <- dm1 |>
  dm_zoom_to(green_df)
```

![](data:image/svg+xml;base64,)

2.  tidyverse pipeline
    ([`mutate()`](https://dplyr.tidyverse.org/reference/mutate.html),
    etc.).

``` r
zoomed_dm2 <- zoomed_dm1 |>
  mutate(var = thing)
```

![](data:image/svg+xml;base64,)

3.  [`dm_update_zoomed()`](https://dm.cynkra.com/dev/reference/dm_zoom_to.md)
    (replace) /
    [`dm_insert_zoomed()`](https://dm.cynkra.com/dev/reference/dm_zoom_to.md)

``` r
dm3 <- zoomed_dm2 |>
  dm_update_zoomed()
```

![](data:image/svg+xml;base64,)

##  Modify database source of a dm

###  Export dm object to database: `copy_dm_to()`

Need a **database connection â€”
[`DBI::dbConnect()`](https://dbi.r-dbi.org/reference/dbConnect.html)**.

``` r
con <- DBI::dbConnect(...)
  # Persistent tables:
persistent_dm <- copy_dm_to(
  con,
  dm1,
  temporary = FALSE
)

DBI::dbDisconnect(con)
```

![](data:image/svg+xml;base64,)

##  Insert, update or remove rows in a dm

Methods:

- `dm_rows_insert(dm1, dm2)`: adds new rows
- `dm_rows_update(dm1, dm2)`: changes values in rows
- `dm_rows_patch(dm1, dm2)`: fills in missing values
- `dm_rows_upsert(dm1, dm2)`: adds new or changes rows
- `dm_rows_delete(dm1, dm2)`: deletes rows

``` r
dm1 |>
  dm_rows_insert(dm2, in_place = FALSE)
```

![](data:image/svg+xml;base64,)![](data:image/svg+xml;base64,)

``` r
dm1 |>
  dm_rows_insert(dm2, in_place = TRUE)
```

![](data:image/svg+xml;base64,)![](data:image/svg+xml;base64,)

A dm is immutable, except with

-  these functions AND
-  a mutable backend (database) AND
-  `in_place = TRUE`.
